XIV.—TERMS EMPLOYED WITH REFERENCE TO MONEY.

TALENTVM, MJNA‚ DRACHMA, OBOL VS, PHILIPPVS s. NVMVS PHILIPPEVS, NVMVS s. NVMVS ARGENTJ.

Ι. Talentum, Mina, Drachma, obolus. As might be expected, considering the source from which the works of Plautus and Terence are derived, the sums of money mentioned in their plays are, for the most part, calculated according to the Greek system of Talents, Minae, and Drachmae.

We may remind the young scholar that these terms all denoted certain weights, and that although the absolute value of each differed in different states, their mutual relation was invariable. Mina may be represented in all cases by the English word Pound, but as the Avoirdupois Pound differs from the Troyes Pound, and both from the Italian Pound, so the Mina of Athens was different in absolute
